Newton's First Law, also known as the Law of Inertia, states that an object at rest will remain at rest, and an object in motion will continue to move with a constant velocity, unless acted upon by an external force.

In other words, if you're sitting on a couch, you'll stay on it unless something pushes or pulls you off. If you're rolling down a hill, you'll keep rolling until friction from the ground or some other external force slows you down.

This law applies to all objects with mass, and it's a fundamental principle in understanding how the universe works. It's often summarized as: "An object will maintain its state of motion unless a force is applied to it."
